sticity is environmentally influenced -- Correlation and interaction between genes and environment -- Developmental risk factors -- Individuals in their environment -- Families And Crime -- Prepubescence : Infancy And Childhood -- Continuity in problem behavior over time -- Postpubescence : Adolescence And Adulthood -- Effects of sexual maturation -- Adolescent development -- Policy Recommendations -- Contextual factors -- Prior to birth -- At birth -- After birth -- Child development -- Adolescence -- Adulthood.  aOverview: Why do individuals exposed to the same environment turn out so differently, with some engaging in crime and others abiding by societal rules and norms? Why are males involved in violent crime more often than females? And why do the precursors of serious pathological behavior typically emerge in childhood? Criminals in the Making: Criminality Across the Life Course, Second Edition, by John Paul Wright, Stephen G. Tibbetts, and Leah E. Daigle, addresses key questions surrounding criminal propensity by discussing studies of the life-course perspective-criminological research that links biological factors associated with criminality with the social and environmental agents thought to cause, facilitate, or otherwise influence a tendency towards criminal activity. The book provides comprehensive, interdisciplinary coverage of the current thinking in the field about criminal behavior over the course of a lifetime. Additionally, it highlights interventions proven effective and illustrates how the life-course perspective has contributed to a greater understanding of the causes of crime.  a29 0aCriminal behavior. 0aCriminology.1 aTibbetts, Stephen G.1 aDaigle, Leah E.  aHV6080 .W74 2015hGMCT-OS-Bi1007423963p70.19kAVAIL_SOON  aHV6080 .W74 2015wLCc1i1007423963d3/22/2017e3/22/2017kCHECKEDOUTlON_SHELFmGR_MACEWANn1p$66.85q1rMsYtBOOKu10/20/201401ahttp://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n2008001805bhttp://viaf.org/viaf/21607663